HEADWORD: Docile
<hw>Doc"ile</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>docilis</ets>,fr. <ets>docere</ets> to teach; cf. Gr. <?/, and L.
<ets>discere</ets> to learn, Gr. <?/ learned, <?/ knowing: cf. F.
<ets>docile</ets>. Cf. <er>Doctor</er>, <er>Didactic</er>,
<er>Disciple</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Teachable; easy to teach;
docible.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Disposed to be taught; tractable; easily managed;
<as>as, a <ex>docile</ex> child</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The elephant is at once docible and <qex>docile</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau> C. J. Smith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Docility</ent>⟦br⟧
